Men whose forefinger is longer than the ring finger , are apparently exposed to a smaller risk , of falling ill with prostate gland cancer .
That is the surprising result of a study which was published by the British Journal of Cancer on Wednesday .
That is supposed to be associated in fact with the level of the masculine hormone testosterone .
Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate gland cancer , and this in particular with men up to sixty , the co-author of the study , Ros Eeles , a professor at the oncology institute at the University of Warwick , declared .
The finger could thus help to determine which men should absolutely subject themselves to a prostate gland cancer test , particularly if genetic risks or other factors of risk exist , for example familiar sanitary problems , Professor Eeles added .
In the period from 1994-2009 , she monitored more than 1500 patients with prostate gland cancer together with her colleagues in Britain , but simultaneously also 3000 healthy men .
With more than half of the participants of the study , the forefinger was shorter on the right hand than the ring finger was .
The same probability of prostate gland cancer was valid for these men as for 19 percent of those men whose ring and forefingers were equally long .
In men whose forefinger was longer than the ring finger this risk sank , however , by around 33 percent , and with men to sixty , even by 87 percent .
